 of Americans? How can elementary and secondary education be distributed consistently with democratic values? The volume confronts powerful criticisms that have been leveled against the welfare state by conservatives, liberals, and radicals and suggests reforms in welfare state programs that might meet these criticisms. The contributors are Joseph H. Carens, Jon Elster, Robert K. Fullinwider, Amy Gutmann, Jennifer L. Hochschild, Stanley Kelley, Jr., Richard Krouse, Michael McPherson, J. Donald Moon, Carole Pateman, Dennis Thompson, and Michael Walzer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aPublic welfarezUnited States. 0aWelfare state. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aBradley, Tom.  aFoundation Programs.  aInequality.  aInvalid Care Allowance (Britain).  aJanowitz, Morris.  aKennedy, Robert.  aKingdon, John.  aMedicaid and Medicare.  aRyan, Alan.  aaccessions tax (Meade).  aaptitudes as resources.  abusiness as election issue.  acivil and legal rights.  aconsumption, behavioral patterns.  adifference principle.  adispersed inequalities.  aenvironment and equality.  aenvy test.  agift relationship.  aguaranteed jobs programs.  ahighway metaphor of citizenship.  ahuman investment, welfare as.  aideology of equal opportunity.  ajob disappearance.  ajury duty.  aleisure, enjoyment of.  aliberty, fair value of.  amoral rights.  anegative income tax.  aovertime work, effects of.  apolitical justice.  apolitical rights.1 aCarens, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElster, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFullinwider, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutmann, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c